[[ch08-handbook-fellowship-of-the-ring]]
== Handbook: Fellowship Of The Ring

Welcome adventurer! Would you like to go on a quest to help Thorin and his party of Dwarves reclaim their ancestral home and treasure, which has been seized by the dragon Smaug?

A little much? How about a quest to learn to dance?

.Twonks Tap
[#img-tap,link=https://irreni.social/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/twonks-tap.jpg] 
image::book/twonks-tap.jpg[Twonks Tap] 

Every quest of some importance requires a company, a fellowship. But how big? Bilbo was recruited as a thief. Or, in modern Dungeons and Dragons terminology, a rogue.

I started playing D&D when it first came out in the early 70s. The standard company size was four people. Generally something like a fighter, a thief, a magic user, and a cleric. But that's kinda small. In that configuration there is no ranged capacity. So perhaps the party would have a fighter, an archer, a magic user and a cleric.

Even a quest to learn how to dance would require a dance instructor and dance partners.

But tap dancing and dragon hunting are not what we are about here. We are about New Democracy.

A couple of observations. First, a quest is declarative. It declares, or states, what needs to be done. It doesn't state how to do the quest. Second you need a company, a fellowship.

Your first quest in New Democracy is to establish a fellowship. In other words, the fellowship is the quest.

Your quest is to find thirty people.

Why thirty people? That seems kinda too many doesn't it?

Well, we don't live in medieval times now. Today a company would need a doctor, a lawyer, communications, marketing, computing, and engineering. Thirty is the number that has just enough roles yet is small enough where everyone has an important role to play.

Further, thirty is a convention and a standard. It is mutually agreed upon for no other reason than to have a standard. Think of thirty like the size of a car today. Cars are designed to fit roads. Roads where initially designed to fit horse-drawn wagons. We're still driving wagons.

The benefit of a convention is that we can build cars and roads anywhere in the world and guarantee new cars, old cars, and cars from different countries can drive on the same roads.

Thirty is not some magic number. It is a convention. The only magic in the number thirty is that it is big enough to contain many professions but small enough that everyone will be important. The only other design feature to note here is that thirty is a number of redundancy. In our 1970s D&D example this would be the equivalent of having a party size of eight. Each role is duplicated. If the healer is injured a backup healer is available.

So adventurer, your quest to begin New Democracy is to establish a, "Fellowship of the Ring." The ring in this case is not a physical ring of magic. The ring is a ring of trust.

When I started doing research for New Democracy I found nothing but abysmal, depressing societal news.

1. Breakdown of the family and work starting in 1900.
2. Breakdown of the neighborhood in 1950.
3. Elimination of the stranger in the 1970s. The Eagles song, "New Kid In Town", was the last pop song about a stranger. :)
4. Loss of the family dinner in the 1990s due to the microwave oven completed the family breakdown.
5. Loss of bowling and bowling alleys virtually overnight in the 1990s.

Lots of uninformed opinions about what's wrong with society today. The fact is societies transitioning from 90% agriculture work before 1900 to only 2% of humans involved in agriculture work by 1980 radically destroyed previous culture leaving nothing durable in its place. Nowadays, all work is being threatened by AI, artificial intelligence.

The quest we all need to undertake then is to build a durable society. A robust and resilient society that can permanently withstand the upheavals of new technology.

That durable society is New Democracy. A society of the people, by the people, and for the people. Permanently. New Democracy uses a mesh design to withstand the test of technological upheaval times. A mesh design is a convention. That convention is simply enough to scale infinitely in time and space. It is simply enough for most humans to understand. Mesh society has two components: MGOs and projects. MGOs, or micro/mesh governing organizations of fixed size thirty. They are the new country, the new nation. These new nations coordinate using projects.

Our first quest then requires us to form a company, an MGO. This is a fellowship of fixed size thirty people. The objective of the quest is to lean to trust.

The breakdown of the family, the neighborhood, and the stranger concept is due to a loss of trust. Today the loss of trust undermines every social institution from governments to news reporting. People wrongly assume that the loss of trust is only due to the desire to exploit people by corruption. No. We've lost both the desire to trust due to corruption as well as the ability to trust.

The Fellowship of the Ring as our first quest is to learn to trust. We must form circles of trust, rings of trust, a fellowship of the ring of trust.

Trust has always involved various rings of trust. Hollywood is convinced the only ring of trust we need is family. The plot of almost everything is some family drama. We do get to see the occasional "No man left behind" ring of trust in some military plots.

New Democracy is not just about establishing a government. New Democracy is about establishing the totality of society. Old Democracy has taught us that the government sitting atop various established societies doesn't build up those societies, it destroys them.

So the responsible thing to do is to have New Democracy encompass or be society.

The quest is to establish a society, an MGO of fixed size thirty people. In some vary real sense an MGO is a castle with a moat. Alligators protect the moat. These castles establish two boundaries:

1. Personal trust
2. Technological advancement defense


We need to rebuild trust. We need to rebuild family units. We need to rebuild the neighborhood. We need to bring back the stranger concept.

An MGO as a nation means those inside the MGO are to be personally trusted. Everyone outside of the MGO not so much. Of course MGOs will have MGO neighbors. This will begin providing natural layers of trust that, like an onion, will have many rings of larger size.

So, our first mission is to form a company of thirty people.

Literally a company. Corporations are people legally in Old Democracies. We are going to use that to our advantage. We are going to start "for life" corporations. These corporations are for supporting life. Perhaps they have business to make profits. That's not the driving purpose. The driving purpose is to establish trust.

This "for life" company can have a medical bay, a dental bay, a legal team, a software team, a manufacturing team. Establishing micro-teams with a few people enables the "for life" company to being to trust the outside world. The MGO trusts its internal legal team. This internal legal team is then used to verify trust of outside legal teams and so on.

If we are going on an adventure then don't we need a dragon to slay? Why, yes we do. That dragon is distrust.

I have always thought of trust as "people programming". Protocols with people to accomplish things are very buggy right now. The main bug is our dragon: distrust.

I think of trust as people programming not as manipulation but as rules for communicating. I'm neurodivergent and social queues don't come naturally. I have to think about them. This means I see trust as protocols of success or failure whereas neurotypicals see trust as personal worth or betrayal. Trust is one of the most emotional mental activities in human behavior. I just happen to be low key emotional about having trust broken being neurotypical. I just see broken trust as broken programming.

So, trust is not just about people being honest and fulfilling commitments. Trust is also about learning to be present in each other's company. That's where I fall down. Being around people drains my emotional batteries and doesn't charge them in any way. That's just who I am.

For me learning to trust people will mostly mean practicing to be present in each other's company.

This brings us to tap dancing. Corporate America has ruined what dancing provides us. They have these "trust" outings where people fall into fellow employee's arms. Or just go on outings. That's now how trust works.

Dancing is not some one time event. Dancing is something we do for life. When we encounter someone else who can dance and then we dance with them we practice trust that includes being present in each other's company. One time events are junk trust.

In some very real sense we need to re-establish dance studios, bowling alleys, and all kinds of social events in order to practice and learn trust.

You see, trust is both a learned thing and a practiced thing.

Side note, so are intellectual things. I'm very good at math. Straight 'A' student and really enjoyed it. However, I don't do math any more, haven't for decades, and when a friend asked me to factor a polynomial as help on his kid's math homework then I was like, uhhh, say what? :)

So trust is an exercise that like physical exercise must be maintained the entirety of one's life. No slacking or we'll get overweight, errr, I mean, distrustful.

So the quest is to establish a fellowship of the ring of trust. Specifically a fixed size thirty person company. The group will form a legal corporation to utilize the benefits of corporations as people for those thirty people. You share Netflix passwords. :)

But also that quest as side quests. Side quests are needed to establish public schools to teach people how to trust. We also have side quests to establish dance studios and bowling alleys to practice the part of trust that requires us to value other people's company instead of hiding behind browser s**t posting.

Personally, I would start with a side quest like establishing a dance studio. Why? Because I believe that only happy people can create a happy productive society. Regardless of the politics of someone like Trump, he's a miserable person and only misery will follow.

We want life to mean something and to enjoy that meaning in the process. Why not work on the enjoyment part first?

We could learn something from the wizard Gandalf from the book, "The Hobbit". You see, one night the fellowship was under threat of being eaten by dire wolves as night was about to set in. Gandalf devised a scheme to shelter in a local Giant's house. The only problem is that giants don't like dwarves. So Gandalf devised a scheme to gradually introduce the twelve dwarves two-by-two. Giants love stories and Gandalf was a great storyteller. He and Bilbo first went into the Giant's house for protection. The Giant agreed for the price of a story. As Gandalf proceeded into the story he would whistle and then introduce the Giant to two more dwarves. The Giant being enthralled with the story begrudgingly agreed to two more dwarves spending the night. Eventually all twelve dwarves were safely inside.

Tap dancing could help our story telling. Dancing could be our enjoyment to smooth over the sharp edges that always cut when beginning to trust new  people for the first time.

So, New Democracy adventurer, are you ready to go on a quest to help thirty people form a company to learn to trust as a society again?
